author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A fighter accused of committing atrocities in Sudan, who was arrested last week by the Rapid Support Forces appears to have been freed from custody.
The RSF said they detained this man, known as "Abu Lulu", on Thursday and transferred him to a prison in el-Fasher.
But since then, other videos have appeared online showing he's been released.
Abu Lulu is accused of posting videos on social media showing executions.

What more do we know about the man known as Abu Lulu and more recently the “Butcher of el-Fasher”?
His real name is al-Fateh Abdullah Idris and he is a Brigadier General in the RSF.
He joined the Rapid Support Forces in 2013 after completing military training and has fought in Yemen several times.
He's also led the Janjaweed militias in Darfur. 
He is said to be close to Mohamed Hamdan Dagalo, widely known as Hemedti, the Commander of the RSF.

Abdallah Hussain is a Sudanese journalist who's been covering this conflict.
He says RSF fighters are using social media as a weapon
title: RSF fighter ‘Abu Lulu’, accused of atrocities in Sudan's el-Fasher, freed

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Democratic candidate Zohran Mamdani has won New York City's mayoral election, defeating independent candidate Andrew Cuomo.
He said voters had ended a political era ruled by the few and pledged to make the city affordable again.

Here are the major pledges Mamdani made on the campaign trail:
He's promised to immediately freeze rent for all stabilised apartments. Those are units where rent increases are regulated by local law.
Mamdani has also promised to enable people to travel for free on city buses. He says one in five New Yorkers struggle to afford the cost of commuting.
He's promised to create a network of city-owned grocery stores focused on keeping prices low.
And Mamdani says he'll implement free universal childcare, for every New Yorker until the age of five.

John Zogby is a public opinion pollster and is a senior partner at John Zogby Strategies. 
He explains the strategy behind Mamdani's victory.

It's in exchange for the body of an Israeli-American soldier that was handed over by Hamas on Tuesday. 
Hamas has promised to return all remaining captives' bodies, under the terms of the ceasefire deal agreed last month.
For every captive returned to Israel, Hamas will receive 15 Palestinian bodies.  

Operations are underway to locate the remains seven more deceased captives, believed to be buried under rubble in Gaza.
Hamas is conducting the search operation alongside the Red Cross. 
The group has warned the scale of destruction from Israel's war is making it difficult to locate and recover the bodies.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Zohran Mamdani was an unlikely frontrunner in New York’s mayoral election. His promise to make life more affordable for working-class New Yorkers, combined with his outspoken criticism of Israel’s crimes against the Palestinian people, earned him a powerful coalition of opponents who poured millions into defeating him. 

Mamdani’s rise also exposed deep divisions within the Democratic Party, whose leadership either declined to endorse him or waited months before doing so. In the end, his campaign served as a litmus test for the growing distance between what voters want and what elected officials and their donors are willing to offer.

Bigger than Zohran takes you inside the battle for New York — and the future of the Democratic Party.
